          <div id="id2" style="height: 1817px; left: 42px; position: absolute; top: 144px; width: 643px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
            <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_643_1817" style="padding: 0px; ">
              <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1">Are you smarter than a Lehman Brothers Trader<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">Q1) Theoretically, what is the main issue in using the Black-Scholes Equation for pricing options on stocks and on baskets composed of those stocks?<br /></p>
                <p class="Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span class="style">Difficulty in calculating the basket forward<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">b) Contradiction between the stock returns and the basket returns both being lognormal<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">c) Valuation of American options<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">d) Estimating the instantaneous basket volatility with a given correlation<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">Q2) Which of these options can be valued by the regular Black-Scholes Equation for European Options (the spot is at 100, American style barrier)?<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2"><br /></p>
                <ol>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="1">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_3"><span style="font-size: 14px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">a)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span class="style">1yr European Call with 110 euro strike call with knock in at 130<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_3"><span style="font-size: 14px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">b)</span><span style="width: 3px; " class="inline-block"></span><span class="style">1yr European Call with 90 euro strike call with knock in at 95<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="3">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_3"><span style="font-size: 14px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">c)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span class="style">1yr European Call with 110 euro strike call with knock in at 80<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="4">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_3"><span style="font-size: 14px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">d)</span><span style="width: 3px; " class="inline-block"></span><span class="style">1yr European Call with 130 euro strike call with knock in at 110<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">Q3) A trader on a cruise is shipwrecked and stranded on a desert island. However, being a dedicated risk manager, he wants to be able simulate a normally distributed variable so that he can manually stress test his trading book back home. Which one of the following should he take to help him do this?<br /></p>
                <p class="Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span class="style">The roulette table from the ship's casino<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">b) Five six-sided dice<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">c) A newspaper with historical data for all the last year's closing prices for the Dow<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">d) Twenty-four one-dollar bills<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">Q4) What is the contradiction in using Black-Scholes to price both options on long-dated interest rates and options on long-dated bonds?<br /></p>
                <p class="Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span class="style"> Interest Rates have no volatility whereas Bonds do <br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">b)  Bonds have no volatilty but Interest Rates do <br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">c)  Hedging of interest rates with bonds is impossible <br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">d)  They both cannot be lognormally distributed <br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">Q5) On any day the market can only go up in steps of $1 or down in steps of $9. Given that out of 10 steps, 9 will be up and 1 will be down. What is the price of a one day ATM digital call paying $1 if the market finishes at a higher level tomorrow than today?<br /></p>
                <p class="Body"><br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span class="style">$0<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">b) $0.9<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">c) $1<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">d) $4.5<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">Q6) For a digital option, why isn't the delta the probability of exercise?<br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span class="style">Because of the pricing of volatility skew is not defined for digital options<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">b) Because of the pricing of forward drift changes the expected carry pnl<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style">c) Because the probability of exercise does not depend on the magnitude of the moves, while the hedge does.<br /></span></p>
                <ol>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="500">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_4"><span style="font-size: 14px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">d)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span class="style">None of the above<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="paragraph_style_5"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_5"><span class="style">Q7) In general, a volatility cap call gives the purchaser<br /></span></p>
                <ol>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="1">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_6"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">a)</span><span style="width: 5px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">High leverage to the underlying during a sequence of sharp upward moves<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_6"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">b)</span><span style="width: 5px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">Low leverage to the underlying during a sequence of sharp downward moves<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="3">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_6"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">c)</span><span style="width: 5px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">High leverage to the underlying for large realized volatilities<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 16px; text-indent: -16px; " class="full-width" value="4">
                    <p style="text-indent: -16px; " class="paragraph_style_6"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">d)</span><span style="width: 5px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">None of the above<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_7"><span style="line-height: 16px; " class="style_2">Q8) </span>Given 5 stocks and all else being equal, which of the following is cheapest?<br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">Basket of atm monthly Asian calls<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">b) Monthly asian atm Himalaya<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">c) atm Himalaya<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">d) Basket of atm American calls<br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_7"><span style="line-height: 16px; " class="style_2">Q9) </span>I run a CPPI structure on an equity underlying where I have no additional borrow facility. If the underlying rallies with high volatility (in a non-monotonic fashion), I expect to make more profit than if I simply held the underlying until maturity.<br /></p>
                <p class="Body">a) <span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">TRUE<br /></span></p>
                <ol>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 15px; text-indent: -15px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                    <p style="text-indent: -15px; " class="paragraph_style_8"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">b)</span><span style="width: 3px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">FALSE<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_7"><span style="line-height: 16px; " class="style_2">Q10) </span>A European digital option pays out if the spot level is above a certain barrier at maturity. Does this option contain risk-reversal risk?<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9">a) <span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">Yes<br /></span></p>
                <ol>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 15px; text-indent: -15px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                    <p style="text-indent: -15px; " class="paragraph_style_8"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">b)</span><span style="width: 3px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">No<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">Answers - Only some...<br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">1) b<br /></span></p>
                <ol>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 15px; text-indent: -15px; " class="full-width" value="2">
                    <p style="text-indent: -15px; " class="paragraph_style_10"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">2)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">d<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 15px; text-indent: -15px; " class="full-width" value="3">
                    <p style="text-indent: -15px; " class="paragraph_style_10"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">3)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">b<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 15px; text-indent: -15px; " class="full-width" value="4">
                    <p style="text-indent: -15px; " class="paragraph_style_10"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">4)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">d<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                  <li style="line-height: 20px; padding-left: 15px; text-indent: -15px; " class="full-width" value="5">
                    <p style="text-indent: -15px; " class="paragraph_style_10"><span style="font-size: 13px; position: relative; top: 1px; " class="Bullet">5)</span><span style="width: 4px; " class="inline-block"></span><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">b<br /></span></p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">8) b - The optionality of a Himalaya is reduced as each asset is removed and it's value fixed. Having a monthly asian Himalaya is paramount to having asianing on an asian option.<br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">9) b - My position is effectively short gamma - I would be selling lows and buying highs - eating in to my capital.<br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1">10) a - Below the barrier the option is long volatility, above the barrier the option is short volatility. If you are long a risk-reversal then you will be long and short vol at different strikes.<br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_9"><span style="line-height: 18px; " class="style_1"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_5"><span style="line-height: 13px; " class="style_3"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_5"><br /></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
                <p class="Body"><span class="style"><br /></span></p>
